{{Otheruses|Taikō as a title|{{ill|Taikō (Nagoya)|ja|太閤 (名古屋市)|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Nakamura-ku, Nagoya|ja|中村区|12=draft|12=draft}}}}
'''Taikō''' (太閤) is a title in Japan referring to a former {{ill|Sesshō|ja|摂政|12=draft|12=draft}} or {{ill|Kampaku|ja|関白|12=draft|12=draft}} who stepped down after transferring the position to their child{{sfn|Hidematsu Wada|1983|p=48}} or someone who, after resigning from the regency, received the imperial {{ill|Senji|ja|宣旨|12=draft|12=draft}} for the title of {{ill|Nairan|ja|内覧|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="#1">{{kotobank|1=Taikō|2=デジタル大辞泉}}</ref><ref name="#2">{{kotobank|1=Taikō|2=日本大百科全書}}</ref>. The honorific for Taikō, like for Sesshō and Kampaku, is "Denka" (殿下), and they are addressed as "Taikō Denka." Historically referred to as '''Taikōka''' (太閤下){{sfn|Hidematsu Wada|1983|p=48}}, the term was later abbreviated. They are also called '''Ōtono''' (大殿){{sfn|Hidematsu Wada|1983|p=48}}.

A Taikō who became a monk is called '''Zenjō Taikō''' (禅定太閤) or simply '''Zenkō''' (禅閤){{sfn|Hidematsu Wada|1983|p=48}}.

== Historical Development ==

=== Early Usage ===
The title initially served as an honorific for sitting Sesshō, Kampaku, and {{ill|Daijō Daijin|ja|太政大臣|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="#1"/><ref name="#2"/>. Records such as the {{ill|Nishinomiya-ki|ja|西宮記|12=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Sakyōki|ja|左経記|12=draft|12=draft}} indicate that active regents were sometimes referred to as Taikō, with phrases like "Kampaku Taikō" appearing{{sfn|Hidematsu Wada|1983|p=49}}.

The practice of referring to retired regents as Taikō began in the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}}. For example, {{ill|Fujiwara no Michinaga|ja|藤原道長|12=draft|12=draft}} was called Taikō after resigning from the position of regent for {{ill|Emperor Go-Ichijō|ja|後一条天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} and subsequently from the office of Daijō Daijin<ref>{{ill|Fujiwara no Sanesuke|ja|藤原実資|12=draft|12=draft}}, ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|小右記|12=draft|12=draft}}'' {{ill|Kannin|ja|寛仁|12=draft|12=draft}} 2, {{ill|June 20 (old calendar)|ja|6月20日|12=draft|12=draft}} entry</ref>. During the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nijō Yoshimitsu|ja|二条良実|12=draft|12=draft}} adopted the title after passing the regency to his brother, {{ill|Ichijō Sanetsune|ja|一条実経|12=draft|12=draft}}, and receiving the Nairan appointment<ref>{{ill|Godaiteiwamonogatari|ja|五代帝王物語|12=draft|12=draft}}</ref>. Similarly, during the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nijō Yoshimoto|ja|二条良基|12=draft|12=draft}} held the title Taikō after a lengthy tenure as Kampaku and receiving the Nairan appointment upon stepping down<ref>{{Cite journal|和書|author=Takeshō Ogawa|date=1995-12|url=https://koara.lib.keio.ac.jp/xoonips/modules/xoonips/detail.php?koara_id=AN00296083-19951200-0001|title=Nijō Yoshimoto’s Appointments: A Study|journal=Mita Kokubun|ISSN=0287-9204|publisher=Keio University|volume=23|pages=1–9|doi=10.14991/002.19951200-0001|naid=110000376031|CRID=1390290699880614784}}</ref>.

=== Toyotomi Hideyoshi and Later Taikō ===
{{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|12=draft|12=draft}} was referred to as Taikō after transferring the Kampaku position to his adopted heir, {{ill|Toyotomi Hidetsugu|ja|豊臣秀次|12=draft|12=draft}}. Even after Hideyoshi's death, the term Taikō became synonymous with him, leading to usages like ''Taikō Kenchi'' (Taikō's Land Survey). This association became so strong that it led to the saying, "''Daishi'' belongs to {{ill|Kūkai|ja|空海|12=draft|12=draft}}, and Taikō belongs to Hideyoshi."

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, other regents who stepped down were also referred to as Taikō. The last individual formally granted the title was {{ill|Takatsukasa Masamichi|ja|鷹司政通|12=draft|12=draft}}, who received the designation in {{ill|Ansei|ja|安政|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 (1857) upon resigning as Kampaku but remaining as Nairan by imperial decree from {{ill|Emperor Kōmei|ja|孝明天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}.

=== Modern Usage: "Now Taikō" ===
With the abolition of the old {{ill|Daijō-kan|ja|太政官制|12=draft|12=draft}} during the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|12=draft|12=draft}}, the title Taikō ceased to exist in its traditional sense. However, figures like {{ill|Itō Hirobumi|ja|伊藤博文|12=draft|12=draft}}, Japan's first Prime Minister, were referred to as "Now Taikō" (今太閤) due to their rise from humble beginnings to prominence, mirroring Hideyoshi. Later, {{ill|Tanaka Kakuei|ja|田中角栄|12=draft|12=draft}}, who became Prime Minister without a university degree, was similarly dubbed "Now Taikō."

The term has since been used more broadly to describe individuals who achieved great power or influence from modest origins. Examples include politicians like {{ill|Miki Bukichi|ja|三木武吉|12=draft|12=draft}}, industrialists like {{ill|Kobayashi Ichizō|ja|小林一三|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Hankyu Railway|ja|阪急電鉄|12=draft|12=draft}}, and entrepreneurs like {{ill|Matsushita Kōnosuke|ja|松下幸之助|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Panasonic|ja|松下電器|12=draft|12=draft}}. Even entertainers such as {{ill|Yoshimoto Sei|ja|吉本せい|12=draft|12=draft}} earned the title, being referred to as "Female Now Taikō."

== Taikō Chronicles ==
Biographies of {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|12=draft|12=draft}} are collectively referred to as the ''{{ill|Taikōki|ja|太閤記|12=draft|12=draft}}''<ref name="ehon">{{Cite journal|和書|author=Kim Jitoku|date=2009-02|url=https://kokubunken.repo.nii.ac.jp/records/730|title=A Commentary on "Ehon Buyū Daikōki"|journal=National Institute of Japanese Literature Bulletin|ISSN=0387-3447|issue=35|pages=209–240|doi=10.24619/00000727|CRID=1390853649821347840}}</ref>. In theater, such as {{ill|Jōruri|ja|浄瑠璃|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kabuki|ja|歌舞伎|12=draft|12=draft}}, the term Taikō is often replaced with ''Daikō'' (大功) in titles like ''Daikōki''<ref name="ehon" />.

