[[sn:Taikō]]
[[ja:太閤]]

{{Otheruses|Taikō as a title|{{ill|Taikō (Nagoya)|ja|太閤 (名古屋市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taikō (Nagoya)|qq=}} in [[:en:Nakamura-ku, Nagoya|Nakamura-ku, Nagoya]]}}
'''Taikō''' (太閤) is a title in Japan referring to a former [[:en:Regent|Sesshō]] or {{ill|Kampaku|ja|関白|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kampaku|qq=}} who stepped down after transferring the position to their child{{sfn|Hidematsu Wada|1983|p=48}} or someone who, after resigning from the regency, received the imperial {{ill|Senji|ja|宣旨|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senji|qq=}} for the title of [[:en:Nairan|Nairan]]<ref name="#1">{{kotobank|1=Taikō|2=デジタル大辞泉}}</ref><ref name="#2">{{kotobank|1=Taikō|2=日本大百科全書}}</ref>. The honorific for Taikō, like for Sesshō and Kampaku, is "Denka" (殿下), and they are addressed as "Taikō Denka." Historically referred to as '''Taikōka''' (太閤下){{sfn|Hidematsu Wada|1983|p=48}}, the term was later abbreviated. They are also called '''Ōtono''' (大殿){{sfn|Hidematsu Wada|1983|p=48}}.

A Taikō who became a monk is called '''Zenjō Taikō''' (禅定太閤) or simply '''Zenkō''' (禅閤){{sfn|Hidematsu Wada|1983|p=48}}.

== Historical Development ==

=== Early Usage ===
The title initially served as an honorific for sitting Sesshō, Kampaku, and [[:en:Daijō-daijin|Daijō Daijin]]<ref name="#1"/><ref name="#2"/>. Records such as the {{ill|Nishinomiya-ki|ja|西宮記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishinomiya-ki|qq=}} and the {{ill|Sakyōki|ja|左経記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakyōki|qq=}} indicate that active regents were sometimes referred to as Taikō, with phrases like "Kampaku Taikō" appearing{{sfn|Hidematsu Wada|1983|p=49}}.

The practice of referring to retired regents as Taikō began in the [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]]. For example, [[:en:Fujiwara no Michinaga|Fujiwara no Michinaga]] was called Taikō after resigning from the position of regent for [[:en:Emperor Go-Ichijō|Emperor Go-Ichijō]] and subsequently from the office of Daijō Daijin<ref>[[:en:Fujiwara no Sanesuke|Fujiwara no Sanesuke]], ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|小右記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}}'' [[:en:Kannin|Kannin]] 2, [[:en:June 20|June 20 (old calendar)]] entry</ref>. During the [[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]], [[:en:Nijō Yoshizane|Nijō Yoshimitsu]] adopted the title after passing the regency to his brother, [[:en:Ichijō Sanetsune|Ichijō Sanetsune]], and receiving the Nairan appointment<ref>{{ill|Godaiteiwamonogatari|ja|五代帝王物語|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Godaiteiwamonogatari|qq=}}</ref>. Similarly, during the [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi period]], [[:en:Nijō Yoshimoto|Nijō Yoshimoto]] held the title Taikō after a lengthy tenure as Kampaku and receiving the Nairan appointment upon stepping down<ref>{{Cite journal|和書|author=Takeshō Ogawa|date=1995-12|url=https://koara.lib.keio.ac.jp/xoonips/modules/xoonips/detail.php?koara_id=AN00296083-19951200-0001|title=Nijō Yoshimoto’s Appointments: A Study|journal=Mita Kokubun|ISSN=0287-9204|publisher=Keio University|volume=23|pages=1–9|doi=10.14991/002.19951200-0001|naid=110000376031|CRID=1390290699880614784}}</ref>.

=== Toyotomi Hideyoshi and Later Taikō ===
[[:en:Toyotomi Hideyoshi|Toyotomi Hideyoshi]] was referred to as Taikō after transferring the Kampaku position to his adopted heir, [[:en:Toyotomi Hidetsugu|Toyotomi Hidetsugu]]. Even after Hideyoshi's death, the term Taikō became synonymous with him, leading to usages like ''Taikō Kenchi'' (Taikō's Land Survey). This association became so strong that it led to the saying, "''Daishi'' belongs to [[:en:Kūkai|Kūkai]], and Taikō belongs to Hideyoshi."

During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], other regents who stepped down were also referred to as Taikō. The last individual formally granted the title was [[:en:Takatsukasa Masamichi|Takatsukasa Masamichi]], who received the designation in [[:en:Ansei|Ansei]] 3 (1857) upon resigning as Kampaku but remaining as Nairan by imperial decree from [[:en:Emperor Kōmei|Emperor Kōmei]].

=== Modern Usage: "Now Taikō" ===
With the abolition of the old {{ill|Daijō-kan|ja|太政官制|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daijō-kan|qq=}} during the [[:en:Meiji Restoration|Meiji Restoration]], the title Taikō ceased to exist in its traditional sense. However, figures like [[:en:Itō Hirobumi|Itō Hirobumi]], Japan's first Prime Minister, were referred to as "Now Taikō" (今太閤) due to their rise from humble beginnings to prominence, mirroring Hideyoshi. Later, [[:en:Kakuei Tanaka|Tanaka Kakuei]], who became Prime Minister without a university degree, was similarly dubbed "Now Taikō."

The term has since been used more broadly to describe individuals who achieved great power or influence from modest origins. Examples include politicians like [[:en:Bukichi Miki|Miki Bukichi]], industrialists like [[:en:Ichizō Kobayashi|Kobayashi Ichizō]] of [[:en:Hankyu|Hankyu Railway]], and entrepreneurs like [[:en:Kōnosuke Matsushita|Matsushita Kōnosuke]] of {{ill|Panasonic|ja|松下電器|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Panasonic|qq=}}. Even entertainers such as {{ill|Yoshimoto Sei|ja|吉本せい|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshimoto Sei|qq=}} earned the title, being referred to as "Female Now Taikō."

== Taikō Chronicles ==
Biographies of [[:en:Toyotomi Hideyoshi|Toyotomi Hideyoshi]] are collectively referred to as the ''[[:en:Taikōki|Taikōki]]''<ref name="ehon">{{Cite journal|和書|author=Kim Jitoku|date=2009-02|url=https://kokubunken.repo.nii.ac.jp/records/730|title=A Commentary on "Ehon Buyū Daikōki"|journal=National Institute of Japanese Literature Bulletin|ISSN=0387-3447|issue=35|pages=209–240|doi=10.24619/00000727|CRID=1390853649821347840}}</ref>. In theater, such as [[:en:Jōruri (music)|Jōruri]] and [[:en:Kabuki|Kabuki]], the term Taikō is often replaced with ''Daikō'' (大功) in titles like ''Daikōki''<ref name="ehon" />.

